Thanks David,
That was what I was trying to say /and/ I think decoupling your code from
EJB specifics and JNDI lookups and EJB-lifecycle events is a good idea. An
EJB container is an execution environment and business logic should not
depend on where it is executing. A combination of JUnit-tests without cactus
and systemtests (executed as a client against the application deployed in a
container works well in our project). The latter is run with our homecooked
acceptance testing framework and the former with junit. This is possible
because our EJB:s are merely shells contining our services that are
implemented as pojos and tested outside the EJB.

It works well for us. Of course there are different ways to skin a cat :)

On 11/3/06, David Saff &lt;saff@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;   Just to clarify, on projects like this, I usually have two levels of
&gt; tests:
&gt; user tests that verify that the end user sees what she expects (running in
&gt; the container, even through the browser), and developer tests that verify
&gt; that my classes work as I expect. For user tests, it&#39;s essential to have
&gt; all the components in place. For developer tests, it&#39;s counter-productive:
&gt; I want to understand what my code does independently of what services are
&gt; provided by third-party containers or servers, and I also want to run
&gt; developer tests often and fast.
&gt;
&gt; I think this is the same thing Vishal is saying below, but I wanted a
&gt; chance
&gt; to rephrase it a little. Thanks,
&gt;
&gt; David Saff
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; On 11/2/06, Vishal Vishnoi &lt;vvishnoi@... &lt;vvishnoi%40bea.com&gt;&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Use Cactus
&gt; &gt; (http://jakarta.apache.org/cactus/writing/howto_testcase.html). It&#39;s
&gt; &gt; very easy to package you test and run them on server side. They also
&gt; &gt; have documentation on how to test EJB or any regular JUnit test in the
&gt; &gt; container.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; For higher level testing (i.e testing like a customer), if you need to
&gt; &gt; verify something in container, then verify it in container. Don&#39;t try to
&gt; &gt; run it outside, otherwise the whole purpose of testing is lost.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; --Vishal
